🎤 Phase 1: Data Harmonization (Elaborated – Speaking Style)

👉 Start:

“In Phase 1, we prepare the data. This is the first and very important step, because good quality data gives better results.”

🔹 Data Acquisition

“First, we collect satellite images. This step is called data acquisition.
We take images from sources like Landsat and Sentinel, which provide images of coastal areas over different time periods.
These images help us study how the shoreline changes over time.”

🔹 Pre-processing

“Next, we do pre-processing.
In this step, we clean the images by removing noise, correcting errors, and improving the quality.
We may also adjust brightness, remove unwanted distortions, and make the images clearer.”

🔹 Harmonization

“After that, we perform harmonization.
This means we make all the images consistent, even if they are taken at different times or from different satellites.
For example, we adjust resolution, scale, and format so that all images can be compared easily.”

👉 End Line (Important)

“So this phase ensures that the data is clean, consistent, and ready for further analysis.”

💡 Extra line (if needed):
👉 “If this step is not done properly, it can affect the accuracy of the final results.”










🎤 Phase 2: Shoreline Extraction (Elaborated – Speaking Style)

👉 Start:

“In Phase 2, we extract the shoreline from the images. This means we identify the boundary between land and water.”

🔹 Feature Engineering

“First, we do feature engineering. In this step, we select important information from the images, like color, texture, and pixel values.
This helps the model to clearly understand the difference between land and water areas.”

🔹 Model Implementation

“Next, we implement the model. Here, we use machine learning or deep learning models like U-Net or Random Forest.
These models are trained to automatically detect and separate land and water regions from the satellite images.”

🔹 Post-processing

“After that, we do post-processing. In this step, we clean the output by removing small errors, smoothing the boundary, and improving the overall quality of the shoreline.”

👉 End Line (Important)

“So in this phase, we clearly separate land and water boundaries and get an accurate shoreline from the images.”

💡 Tip:
If teacher asks more, just add this line:
👉 “This step is very important because accurate shoreline extraction is needed for correct erosion analysis.”












🎤 Phase 3: Predictive Modelling (Elaborated – Speaking Style)

👉 Start:

“In Phase 3, we predict future shoreline changes. This helps us understand how the coastline will change over time.”

🔹 Time-Series Construction

“First, we construct time-series data.
In this step, we arrange shoreline data from different years in order, like past to present.
This helps us understand the pattern of how the shoreline has been changing over time.”

🔹 Comparative Forecasting

“Next, we do comparative forecasting.
Here, we use machine learning models to compare past changes and predict future shoreline positions.
This helps us estimate whether erosion or accretion will happen in the future.”

🔹 Accuracy Assessment

“Finally, we check the accuracy of our predictions.
We use evaluation methods like F1-score or IoU to see how correct our model predictions are.”

👉 End Line (Important)

